    1. Given array arr, we first consider the greatest fractions that could be generated using elements from arr (i.e., num/denom). The products of these fractions are stored in a priority queue (min-heap).
2. Then we iterate k-1 times to find the k-th smallest fraction from the priority queue:
  a. Pop the smallest fraction from the priority queue and decrease the denominator of that fraction.
  b. Push the new fraction back into the priority queue.
3. Finally, after iterating k-1 times, the current smallest fraction (top of priority queue) will be the k-th smallest fraction in the array. We return the corresponding numerator and denominator as the output.

